<section xml:id="sec_Permutations_CycleAlgebraicProperties">
  <title>Algebraic properties of cycles <nbsp/><nbsp/></title>
  <figure>
    <video youtubeplaylist="PL2uooHqQ6T7PW5na4EX8rQX2WvBBdM8Qo"/>
  </figure>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec_Permutations_CycleAlgebraicProperties_DefinitionOfOrder">
    <title>Powers of cycles: definition of order</title>
    <p>
      Let's revisit the product of cycles.
      We will look at what happens when you compose a cycle with itself multiple times.
          <idx><h>Cycle</h><h>powers of</h></idx>
    </p>
    <example xml:id="example_Permutations_cycle_squared">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the product <m>(1264)(1264)</m>,
          which we may also write as <m>(1264)^2</m>.
          As in the previous section, we can use a diagram
          (see <xref ref="fig_perm_square">Figure</xref>)
          to compute this product.
          But let's try to understand better what's really going on.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig_perm_square">
          <caption>Diagram of <m>(1264)^2</m>, showing in particular how the permutation takes 1 to 6.</caption>
          <image width="37%" source="images/perm_square.png"/>
        </figure>
        <ol type="1">
          <li>
            <p>
              Notice for all elements <m>x \neq 1, 2, 6, 4</m>,
              <m>x</m> stays put in <m>(1264)</m>;
              hence <m>x</m> stays put in <m>(1264)^2</m>.
              So the product <m>(1264)^2</m> does not involve any elements except <m>1, 2, 6</m> and <m>4</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Now let's look at what happens when <m>x = 1, 2, 6</m>,
              or <m>4</m>.
              By squaring the cycle, we are applying it twice to each input;
              hence each input is moved two spots around the wheel
              (see <xref ref="fig_perm_square2">Figure</xref>)
              .  In other words,
              <me>
                1 \to 6;   6 \to 1;  2 \to 4;  4 \to 2
              </me>,
              Altogether: <m>(1264)^2 = (16)(24)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <figure xml:id="fig_perm_square2">
          <caption><m>(1264)^2</m>: streamlined notation</caption>
          <image width="15%" source="images/perm_square2.png"/>
        </figure>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      With this methodology in mind,
      let's explore powers of cycles a bit further.
    </p>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_4th_power">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute each of the following.
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 2 6 4)^3</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 2 6 4)^4</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 2 6 4)^5</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_6th_power">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute each of the following:
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 2 5 8 4 3)^2</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 2 5 8 4 3)^3</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 2 5 8 4 3)^4</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 2 5 8 4 3)^5</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 2 5 8 4 3)^6</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 2 5 8 4 3)^7</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      Do you notice a pattern from these two exercises?
      Let us investigate in a bit more detail:
      this will help us build up towards a proof of a general statement.
    </p>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_power_of_n-cycle1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>X = \{1,2,\ldots,10\}</m>,
          let <m>A = \{2,5,7,8\}</m>,
          and let <m>\sigma \in S_X</m> be the cycle <m>\sigma = ( 2 5 7 8 )</m>.
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                What is <m>\sigma(2)</m>?
                What is <m>\sigma^2(2)</m>?
                What is <m>\sigma^3(2)</m>?
                What is <m>\sigma^4(2)</m> What is <m>\sigma^{3,482,991}(2)?</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                What is <m>\sigma(5)</m>?
                What is <m>\sigma^2(5)</m>?
                What is <m>\sigma^3(5)</m>?
                What is <m>\sigma^4(5)</m> What is <m>\sigma^{3,482,991}(5)?</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Fill in the blank: If <m>x \in A</m> then <m>\sigma^k(x) = \sigma^{\bmod(k,\underline{~~})}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                What is <m>\sigma(1)</m>?
                What is <m>\sigma(3)</m>?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                What general statement can you make about
                <m>\sigma^k(x)</m> for <m>x \in X \backslash A</m>?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                * Let <m>K = \{k: \sigma^k(x) = x ~~\forall x \in X\}</m>.
                Is <m>2 \in K</m>?
                Is <m>3 \in K</m>?
                Is <m>4 \in K</m>?
                Given any positive integer <m>k</m>,
                what's a simple way of telling whether or not <m>k \in K</m>?
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      Hopefully you're beginning to see the picture!
      To generalize these results, we need some additional terminology:
    </p>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          {defordercycle} The <term>order</term>
          of a cycle <m>\sigma</m> is the smallest natural number <m>k</m> such that <m>\sigma^k = {\var id}</m>.
              <idx><h>Cycle</h><h>order of</h></idx>
              <idx><h>Order</h><h>of a cycle</h></idx>
          The order of <m>\sigma</m> is denoted by the notation <m>|\sigma|</m>.<fn>
          This is in keeping with our practice of using <m>|\ldots|</m> to denote the
          <q>size</q>
          of things.
          </fn>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      After that long build-up, we now have (Ta-da!):
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="proposition_Permutations_order_of_cycle">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The order of a cycle is always equal to the cycle's length.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
    <proof>
      <p>
        To prove this, we essentially have to prove two things:
        <ol type="A">
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>\sigma</m> is a cycle of length <m>k</m>,
              then <m>\sigma^k = {\var id}</m>;
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>\sigma</m> is a cycle of length <m>k</m>,
              then <m>\sigma^j \neq {\var id}</m><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><m>\forall j: 1 \le j \lt k</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      <p>
        The proof for (A) follows the same lines as our investigations in <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_power_of_n-cycle1">Exercise</xref>.
        In that exercise,
        we considered separately the elements of <m>X</m> that are moved by the cycle,
        and those elements that are not moved by the cycle.
      </p>
      <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_length_equals_order">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove part (A) by filling in the blanks.
          </p>
          <p>
            Let <m>\sigma \in S_X</m> be an arbitrary cycle of length <m>k</m>.
            Then <m>\sigma</m> can be written as <m>(a_1 \, a_2 \, \ldots \, a_k)</m>,
            for some set of elements <m>a_1, a_2, \ldots a_k</m> in <m>X</m>.
            In order to show that <m>\sigma^k = {\var id}</m>,
            it is sufficient to show that <m>\sigma^k(x) = \underline{~\lt 1>~} \forall x \in X</m>.
            Let <m>A</m> be the set <m>\{a_1, a_2, \ldots a_k\}</m>.
            Now for any <m>x \in X</m>, there are two possibilities:
            <ol type="i">
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>x \in X \backslash A</m>;
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>x \in A</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
          <p>
            We'll deal with these two cases separately
            (as we did in <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_power_of_n-cycle1">Exercise</xref>).
            <ol type="i">
              <li>
                <p>
                  In this case,
                  <m>\sigma(x) = \underline{~\lt 2>~}</m> It follows that <m>\sigma^2(x) = \sigma( \sigma(x)) = \sigma( \underline{~\lt 3>~}) = \underline{~\lt 4>~}</m>.
                  We can use the same argument to show that <m>\sigma^3(x) = \underline{~\lt 5>~}</m>,
                  and that <m>\sigma^k(x) = \underline{~\lt 6>~}</m> for any natural number <m>\underline{~\lt 7>~}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  In this case,
                  then <m>x = a_j</m> for some integer <m>j, 1 \le j \le \underline{~\lt 8>~}</m>.
                  It follows from the definition of cycle that <m>\sigma(x) = \sigma(a_j) = a_{\bmod(j+1,k)}</m>.
                  Furthermore,
                  <m>\sigma^2(x) = \sigma(a_{\bmod(j+1,k)}) = \underline{~\lt 9>~}</m>.
                  Similarly it follows that <m>\sigma^{k}(x) = a_{\bmod(j+ \underline{~\lt 10>~},k)} = a_{\underline{~\lt 11>~}} = x</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
          <p>
            Cases (i) and (ii) establish that <m>\forall x \in X, \underline{~\lt 12>~} = x</m>.
            It follows that <m>\sigma^k = \underline{~\lt 13>~}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <p>
        The proof of (B) is also structured as an exercise.
      </p>
      <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_length_equals_order2">
        <statement>
          <p>.
            In this exercise we use the same notation as part (A), that is:
            <m>\sigma \in S_X</m> has length <m>k</m> and is represented as:
            <m>\sigma = (a_1 \, a_2 \, \ldots \, a_k)</m>.
            <ol type="a">
              <li>
                <p>
                  What is <m>\sigma(a_1)</m>?
                  What is <m>\sigma^2(a_1)</m>?
                  What is <m>\sigma^3(a_1)</m>?
                  What is <m>\sigma^{k-1}(a_1)</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Conclude from part (a) that
                  <m>\sigma^j \neq {\var id}</m> for <m>j = 1,2,3, \ldots, k-1</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </proof>
    <example xml:id="example_Permutations_cycle_order">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Here's a nice application of <xref ref="proposition_Permutations_order_of_cycle">Proposition</xref>,
          which simply uses rules of function composition.
          This should also give you a good start on the next exercise.
          <me>
            (1 2 6 4)^6 = (1 2 6 4)^4 (1 2 6 4)^2 = {\var id} ~(1 6) (2 4) = (1 6)(2 4)
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_cycle_order_1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute the following:
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 2 6 4)^{11}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 2 5 8 4 3)^{53}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(3 5 2)(1 3 6)(1254)^{102}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(3 4 8) (4 5 6)^5 (1 3 2 5)^{10}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_Ad4">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>\sigma</m> is a cycle of odd length,
          prove that <m>\sigma^2</m> is also a cycle. (*Hint*)
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec_Permutations_CycleAlgebraicProperties_PowerAndOrderGeneral">
    <title>Powers and orders of permutations in general</title>
    <p>
      Now that we know the order of cycles,
      let's see if we can tackle other permutations as well:
    </p>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          {deforder} The <term>order</term>
          of a permutation <m>\tau</m> is the smallest positive integer <m>k</m> such that <m>\tau^k = {\var id}</m>.
              <idx><h>Order</h><h>of a permutation</h></idx>
          As before, the order of <m>\tau</m> is denoted by the notation <m>|\tau|</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      <em>Proposition</em>: Let <m>\tau</m> be a permutation,
      and let <m>k = |\tau|</m>.
      Then <m>\tau^{\ell} = {\var id}</m> if and only if <m>\mod(\ell,k)=0</m>.
    </p>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_64">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Fill in the blanks with the appropriate variables in the following proof of the proposition. (*Hint*)
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Proof:</em> For any integer <m>\ell</m> we may write <m>\ell = ak + b</m>,
          where <m>b \in \mathbb{Z}_{\underline{~\lt 1>~}}</m>.
          It follows that
          <me>
            \tau^{\ell} = \tau^{\lt \underline{2}> \cdot k + \lt \underline{3}>} = (\tau^{\lt \underline{4}> \cdot k})\tau^{\lt \underline{5}>} =   (\tau^k)^{\lt \underline{6}>}\tau^{\lt \underline{7}>} = ({\var id})^{\lt \underline{8}>}\tau^{\lt \underline{9}>} = \tau^{\lt \underline{10}>}
          </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Therefore <m>\tau^{\ell} = {\var id}</m> if and only if <m>\tau^{\lt \underline{11}>} = {\var id}</m>.
          However, we know that <m>\underline{~\lt 12>~} \lt k</m>,
          and we also know that <m>\underline{~\lt 13>~}</m> is the smallest positive integer such that <m>\tau^{\lt \underline{14}>} = {\var id}</m>.
          Hence it must be the case that <m>b= \underline{~\lt 15>~}</m>,
          which is the same thing as saying that <m>\bmod(\ell,\underline{~\lt 17>~})=0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      Can we characterize the order of a permutation that is a product of disjoint cycles?
      Let's explore.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="example_Permutations_disjoint_squared">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\tau = (2 4)(1 6)</m>.
          Notice that <m>(2 4)</m> and <m>(1 6)</m> are disjoint,
          so they commute
          (recall <xref ref="proposition_Permutations_disjoint_cycles_commute">Proposition</xref>).
          We also know that permutations are associative under composition.
          So we may compute <m>\tau^2</m> as follows:
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>\tau^2 = \Big( (2 4 )(1 6 ) \Big) \Big( (2 4 )(1 6 ) \Big)</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          <nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>=
          <m>(2 4) {\Big(} (1 6) (2 4 ) {\Big )} (1 6 )</m><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>(associative)
        </p>
        <p>
          <nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>=
          <m>(2 4 ) {\Big(} (2 4 ) (1 6) {\Big )} (1 6 )</m><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>(commutative)
        </p>
        <p>
          <nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>=
          <m>{\Big(} (2 4 ) (2 4 ) {\Big )} {\Big(} (1 6) (1 6 ) {\Big )}</m><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>(associative)
        </p>
        <p>
          <nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>=
          <m>{\var id}~{\var id}</m> <nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>(2-cycles have order 2)
        </p>
        <p>
          <nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>= <m>{\var id}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_disjoint_cube">
      <statement>
        <ol type="a">
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>\sigma = (237)</m> and <m>\tau = (458)</m>.
              By following the format of <xref ref="example_Permutations_disjoint_squared">Example</xref>,
              show that <m>(\sigma \tau)^3 = {\var id}</m>
              (write out each step, and cite the property used).
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              * If <m>\sigma</m> and <m>\tau</m> are disjoint cycles with <m>|\sigma| = |\tau| = k</m>,
              what may you conclude about
              <m>| \sigma \tau |</m>? (You don't need to give a proof).
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      Associativity and commutativity are powerful tools for rearranging products of disjoint cycles,
      and bear in mind that any disjoint cycles commute.
    </p>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_k_power_disjoint_cycles">
      <statement>
        <ol type="a">
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>\sigma</m> and <m>\tau</m> be <em>any</em>
              disjoint cycles. using associative and commutative properties (see <xref ref="proposition_Permutations_disjoint_cycles_commute">Proposition</xref>,
              show that <m>(\sigma \tau)^2 = \sigma^2 \tau^2</m>
              (write out each step, and cite the property used).
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>\sigma</m> and <m>\tau</m> are disjoint cycles and <m>k</m> is a natural number,
              what may you conclude about
              <m>(\sigma \tau)^k</m> in terms of powers of <m>\sigma</m> and <m>\tau</m>? (You don't need to give a proof).
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_disjoint_order_1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose then <m>\tau = (1 2 3)( 4 5)</m>.
          Compute each of the following
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\tau^2</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\tau^3</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\tau^4</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\tau^5</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\tau^6</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\tau^7</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      Notice what happened to the disjoint cycles in the previous exercise.
      For instance <m>|(1 2 3)| = 3</m>,
      and in parts (a)-(f) of the exercise you had the repeating pattern <m>\{(1 3 2), {\var id}, (1 2 3), (1 3 2), {\var id}, \ldots\}</m>.
      Similarly, the 2-cycle <m>(4 5)</m> yielded the repeating pattern <m>\{{\var id}, (4 5), {\var id}, (4 5) \ldots \}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      In <m>\tau^3, \tau^6, \tau^9, \ldots</m> the
      <m>(1 2 3)^k</m> part of <m>\tau^k</m> becomes <m>{\var id}</m>,while in
      <m>\tau^2, \tau^4, \tau^6, \ldots</m> the <m>(4 5)^k</m> part becomes <m>{\var id}</m>.
      In order for <m>\tau^k = {\var id}</m>,
      we must have both <m>(1 2 3)^k = {\var id}</m> and <m>(4 5)^k = {\var id}</m>,
      which first happens when <m>k = 6</m>.
      Which is the least common multiple of 2 and 3.
      Which makes sense.
      To visualize this idea,
      think about the question posed in the following figure:
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig_wheels_2">
      <caption>How many times does the small gear (at left) need to turn to return all gears to their original position? (Each turn rotates all  gears clockwise by 1 position.)</caption>
      <image width="65%" source="images/wheels1.png"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Disjoint cycles are like gears,
      so they should first align back at
      <q>1</q>, or <m>id</m>, when they've been
      <q>turned</q>
      a number of times that is precisely the least common multiple of the number of teeth on the gears.
      The order of a permutation of disjoint cycles should just be the least common multiple of the orders of it's respective cycles.
    </p>
    <p>
      In fact, we can prove it.
      We will start with two disjoint cycles:
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="proposition_Permutations_order_of_2disjoint_cycles">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>\sigma</m> and <m>\tau</m> are disjoint cycles, then
          <me>
            |\sigma \tau| = \mbox{ lcm } (|\sigma|,|\tau|)
          </me>,
          where <sq>lcm</sq> denotes least common multiple.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Let <m>j \equiv |\sigma|, k \equiv |\tau|</m>,
        and <m>m \equiv \mbox{ lcm } (k,j)</m>.
        Then it's enough to prove:
        <ol type="i">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>(\sigma \tau)^m = {\var id}</m>;
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>(\sigma \tau)^n \neq {\var id}</m> if <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m> and <m>n \lt m</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      <p>
        To prove (i), first note that <m>k</m> divides <m>m</m>,
        so that <m>m = j \cdot p</m> for some natural number <m>p</m>.
        Similarly, <m>m = k \cdot q</m> for some <m>q \in \mathbb{N}</m>.
        It follows:
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>(\sigma \tau )^m = \sigma^m \tau^m</m><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>(by <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_k_power_disjoint_cycles">Exercise</xref>)
      </p>
      <p>
        <nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><m>= \sigma^{j \cdot p} \tau^{ k \cdot q}</m><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>(by definition of lcm)
      </p>
      <p>
        <nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>
        <m>= (\sigma^j)^p (\tau^ k)^q</m><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>(by exponentiation rules)<fn>
        These are the same exponentiation rules you saw in high school algebra:
        <m>x^{ab} = (x^a)^b</m>
        </fn>
      </p>
      <p>
        <nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><m>= {\var id} ^p {\var id} ^q</m><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>(by definition of order)
      </p>
      <p>
        <nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><m>= {\var id}</m><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>(by definition of <m>{\var id}</m>).
      </p>
      <p>
        To prove (ii), let <m>n \lt m</m>.
        It follows either <m>k</m> or <m>j</m> does
        <em>not</em> divide <m>n</m>.
        Let's suppose it's <m>k</m>
        (the case where it's <m>j</m> is virtually identical).
        In this case we must have <m>n = p \cdot k + r</m> where <m>p</m>,r<m>\in \mathbb{N}</m> and <m>r \lt k</m>.
        It follows:
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>(\sigma \tau )^n = \sigma^n \tau^n</m><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>(by <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_k_power_disjoint_cycles">Exercise</xref>)
      </p>
      <p>
        <nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><m>= \sigma^{j \cdot p + r} \tau^n</m><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>(substitution)
      </p>
      <p>
        <nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>
        <m>= (\sigma^j)^p \sigma^r \tau^n</m><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>(by exponentiation rules)
      </p>
      <p>
        <nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><m>= {\var id} ^p \sigma^r \tau^n</m><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>(by definition of order)
      </p>
      <p>
        <nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><m>= \sigma^r \tau^n</m><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>(by definition of identity)
      </p>
      <p>
        Now since <m>r \lt k</m>,
        and <m>|\sigma| = k</m>, it follows that <m>\sigma^r \neq {\var id}</m>.
        Thus there is some <m>x</m> such that <m>\sigma^r(x) \neq x</m>.
        But since <m>\sigma</m> and <m>\tau</m> are disjoint,
        it must be the case that <m>\tau(x) = x</m>.
        It follows that:
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>\sigma^r \tau^n (x) = \sigma^r (x) \neq x</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        From this we may conclude that <m>(\sigma \tau )^n</m> is
        <em>not</em> the identity.
        This completes the proof of
        (ii).
      </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
      What <xref ref="proposition_Permutations_order_of_2disjoint_cycles">Proposition</xref>
      establishes for two disjoint cycles is also true for multiple disjoint cycles.
      We state the proposition without proof,
      because it is similar to that of <xref ref="proposition_Permutations_order_of_2disjoint_cycles">Proposition</xref> except with more details.
          <idx><h>Disjoint cycles</h><h>powers of</h></idx>
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="proposition_Permutations_order_of_disjoint">
      <statement>
        <p>
              <idx><h>Order</h><h>disjoint cycles</h></idx>
              <idx><h>Disjoint cycles</h><h>order of</h></idx>
          Suppose <m>\sigma_1, \sigma_2, \ldots , \sigma_n</m> are <m>n</m> disjoint cycles, where <m>k_1, k_2, \ldots, k_n</m> are the lengths, respectively, of the <m>n</m> disjoint cycles.
          Then
          <me>
            |\sigma_1 \sigma_2  \cdots \sigma_n| = \mbox{ lcm } (k_1, k_2, \ldots, k_n)
          </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
    <p>
      Now we can find the order of any permutation by first representing it as a product of disjoint cycles.
    </p>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_Sn_orders">
      <statement>
        <p>
          What are all the possible orders for the permutations in each of the following sets
          (look back at your work for <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_cycle_types">Exercise</xref>).
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>S_6</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>S_7</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>S_8</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_disjoint_order_2">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute the following:
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>| (1 2 5 4)^2 |</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>| (1 3 6 5 8)^2 (4 7 3)^2 (1 2 5) |</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>| (1 3 6 5 8)^{13} (1 2 5 4)^{11} (4 7 3) |</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>| (1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 9)^{300} |</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
