    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\sigma</m> be a permutation in <m>S_n</m>.
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                Show that there exists an integer <m>k>1</m> such that <m>\sigma^k = \sigma</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Show that there exists an integer <m>\ell>1</m> such that <m>\sigma^{\ell} = \sigma^{-1}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>K</m> be the set of <em>all</em>
                integers <m>k>1</m> such that <m>\sigma^k = \sigma</m>.
                Show that <m>K</m> is an infinite set
                (that is, <m>K</m> has an infinite number of elements).
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>L</m> be the set of <em>all</em>
                integers <m>\ell>1</m> such that <m>\sigma^{\ell} = \sigma^{-1}</m>.
                Show that <m>L</m> is an infinite set.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                What is the relationship between the sets <m>K</m> and <m>L</m>?
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec_Permutations_CycleAlgebraicProperties_TranspositionAndInverses">
    <title>Transpositions and inverses</title>
    <p>
      The simplest nontrivial cycles are those of length 2.
      We will show that these 2-cycles are convenient
      <q>building blocks</q>
      which can be used to construct all other cycles.
    </p>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          {Transposition} Cycles of length 2 are called
          <term>transpositions</term>.
              <idx><h>Transposition</h><h>definition of</h></idx>
              <idx><h>Cycle</h><h>transposition</h></idx>
          We will often denote transpositions by the symbol <m>\tau</m> (the greek letter
          <q>tau</q>).
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_example_transpositions">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute the following products:
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 4)(1 3) (1 2)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 4)(1 8) (1 9)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 6)(1 5) (1 4)(1 3)(1 2)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(4 9)(4 8) (4 7)(4 6)(4 5)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 2)(1 3)(1 4)(1 5) (1 6)(1 7)(1 8)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_example_transpositions2">
      <statement>
        <p>
          In light of what you discovered in the previous exercise,
          write each cycle as a product of transpositions:
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 4 9 2)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 2 3 4 5)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(4 7 2 5 6 3)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(a_1 a_2 a_3)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(a_1 a_2 a_3 a_5 a_6)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(a_1 a_2 a_3 a_5 a_6 a_7 a_8)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      The preceding exercises demonstrate the following proposition:
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="proposition_Permutations_transposition_formula">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every cycle can be written as the product of transpositions:<idx><h>Cycle</h><h>as products of transpositions</h></idx>
          <me>
            (a_1, a_2, \ldots, a_n ) = (a_1 a_n ) (a_1 a_{n-1} ) \cdots ( a_1 a_3 ) (a_1 a_2 )
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
    <proof>
      <p>
        The proof involves checking that left and right sides of the equation agree when they act on any <m>a_j</m>.
        We know that the cycle acting on <m>a_j</m> gives <m>a_{j+1}</m> (or <m>a_1</m>,
        if <m>j = n</m>);
        while the product of transpositions sends <m>a_j</m> first to <m>a_1</m>,
        then to <m>a_{j+1}</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
      Recall that we also know that any permutation can be written as a product of disjoint cycles,
      which leads to:
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="proposition_Permutations_trans_perm">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Any permutation of a finite set containing at least two elements can be written as the product of transpositions.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
    <proof>
      <p>
        First write the permutation as a product of cycles:
        then write each cycle as a product of transpositions.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_prod_of_trans_1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Express the following permutations as products of transpositions.
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>( 1 4 3 5 6 )</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>( 1 5 6 )( 2 3 4 )</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>( 1 4 2 6 )( 1 4 2 )</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>( 1 7 2 5 4 )( 1 4 2 3 )( 1 5 4 6 3 2 )</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>( 1 4 2 6 3 7 )(2 3 5 9)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>( 1 3 5 7 9 )(2 4 6 8 ) (1 9 7 5 3) (2 8 6 4)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      Even the identity permutation
      <m>{\var id}</m> can be expressed as the product of transpositions:<idx><h>Identity</h><h>of transpositions</h></idx>
    </p>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_prod_of_trans_2">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute the following products:
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 2) (1 2)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(5 7)(5 7)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(a_1 a_2)(a_1 a_2)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                What can you conclude about the inverse of a transposition?
                  <idx><h>Inverse</h><h>of transpositions</h></idx>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      The preceding exercise amounts to a proof of the following:
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="proposition_Permutations_trans_inv">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>\tau</m> is a transposition, <m>\tau^{-1} = \tau</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
    <p>
      We can use the inverses of transpositions to build up the inverses of larger cycles:
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="proposition_Permutations_cycle_inv">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>\mu</m> is a cycle:
          <m>\mu = (a_1 a_2 \ldots a_n)</m>.
          Then <m>\mu^{-1} = (a_1 a_n a_{n-1} \ldots a_2 )</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
    <proof>
      <p>
        By <xref ref="proposition_Permutations_transposition_formula">Proposition</xref> we can write
        <me>
          \mu = (a_1 a_n ) (a_1 a_{n-1} ) \cdots ( a_1 a_3) (a_1 a_2)
        </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now consider first just the last two transpositions in this expression.
        In the Functions chapter,
        we proved the formula <m>(f \compose g)^{-1} = g^{-1} \compose f^{-1}</m> for invertible functions <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>.
        Since transpositions are invertible functions, we have
        <me>
          {\Big(}(a_1 a_3)(a_1 a_2){\Big)}^{-1} = (a_1 a_2)^{-1} ( a_1 a_3)^{-1} = (a_1 a_2 ) (a_1 a_3 )
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        (the second equality follows because every transposition is its own inverse.)
      </p>
      <p>
        If we apply similar reasoning to the last three transpositions in the expression, we find
        <me>
          {\Big(}(a_1 a_4)(a_1 a_3)(a_1 a_2){\Big)}^{-1} = [(a_1 a_3)(a_1 a_2)]^{-1} ( a_1 a_4)^{-1} = (a_1 a_2 ) (a_1 a_3 ) (a_1 a_4)
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Applying this result inductively, we obtain finally:
        <me>
          \mu^{-1} = (a_1 a_2) ( a_1 a_3) \cdots (a_1 a_{n-1} ) (a_1 a_n )
        </me>,
        from this expression we may see that <m>a_1 \rightarrow a_n</m>,
        <m>a_n \rightarrow a_{n-1}, a_{n-1} \rightarrow a_{n-2}, \ldots,
        a_{2} \rightarrow a_{1}</m>, which corresponds to the cycle we want.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
      Because the product of permutations is an associative operation,
      we may find the inverse of any product of cycles by taking the inverses of the cycles in reverse order.
          <idx><h>Inverse</h><h>of a cycle</h></idx>
          <idx><h>Cycle</h><h>inverse of</h></idx> (Actually, this is just a special case of the inverse of function composition: <m>(f_1 \circ f_2 \circ \ldots \circ f_{n-1}\circ f_n)^{-1}= f_n^{-1} \circ f_{n-1}^{-1} \circ \ldots \circ f_2 \circ f_1</m>.)
    </p>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\left[ ( 1 4 9 8 )( 2 4 6 8 ) \right] ^{-1} = ( 2 4 6 8 )^{-1}( 1 4 9 8 )^{-1} = ( 2 8 6 4 )(1 8 9 4) = ( 1 6 4)( 2 8 9)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>( 1 3 5 7) ^{-2} = \left[ ( 1 3 5 7 )^{-1} \right]^2 = ( 1 7 5 3 )^2 = ( 1 7 5 3 )(1 7 5 3) = ( 1 5 )(3 7)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_inv_comps">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate each of the following.
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(1 2 5 3 7)^{-1}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>[(1 2)(3 4)(1 2)(4 7)]^{-1}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>[( 1 2 3 5 )( 4 6 7 )]^{-2}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>( 1 2 5 4 )^{-1} ( 1 2 3 )( 4 5 ) ( 1 2 5 4 )</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>( 1 2 3 )( 4 5 ) ( 1 2 5 4 )^{-2}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>( 7 4 2 )^{-7} ( 2 8 6)^{-13}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Permutations_cycleSTructureOfInverse">
      <statement>
        <p>
          In <xref ref="subsec_Permutations_CycleNotation_CycleStructure">Section</xref>
          we introduced the notion of the
          <q>cycle structure</q>
          of a permutation.
          Using some of the ideas that we have introduced in this section,
          prove that if <m>\sigma</m> is any permutation,
          then <m>\sigma^{-1}</m> has the <em>same</em>
          cycle structure as <m>\sigma</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>
</section>